{
  "doc_id": "25298",
  "text": "One edge node strategy that has the potential to improve burst contention significantly, especially when wavelength conversion is unavailable or sparse, is wavelength assignment. A priority wavelength selection algorithm was presented in [CITATION_1] , and a comprehensive study of wavelength selection strategies for OBS networks can be found in [CITATION_2] . An algorithm for buffering bursts electronically at edge nodes and scheduling them to prevent burst overlap at links inside the network was proposed in [CITATION_3] . A traffic engineering approach to select paths for source routing to balance the traffic load across the network links was investigated in [CITATION_4] . Finally, a dynamic scheme for selecting routes at the burst sources was proposed in [CITATION_5] . Each source maintains a (short) list of alternate paths to each destination and uses link congestion information to rank each path. The source uses the least congested path to transmit its bursts. We note that a similar technique, referred to as \"endto-end path switching,\" was proposed and evaluated recently for selecting one among a set of Internet paths [CITATION_6] ; the main finding was that path switching can result in improvement in packet loss.",
